Everyone’s panicking about AI being a threat to learning.

But honestly? The real threat is confusion.

Students are juggling syllabi, capstone guidelines or course packets, assignment prompts, lecture slides — all with different rules, deadlines, and expectations.

That’s why I’ve partnered with @adobeacrobat . AI Assistant helps turn all that academic chaos into clear answers.

No more last-minute emails. No more guessing. Just students who actually know what they’re supposed to do.

@z_.angelo Counterpoint: I’ve been using Adobe products to help me create stuff for over 20 years. Most of your favorite creators probably use Adobe in some way, too — they’re an anchor of the creative industry. In other words, all that “previously good content” you’ve enjoyed exists, in part, thanks to Adobe. So when Adobe reaches out and says, “Hey… we’ve got this thing we think is cool and we’d like your help telling people about it,” a lot of us are going to be interested because Adobe has been the backbone of our work and industry for so long.

As for what that “cool thing” is… my stance on AI in academia is pretty obvious from lots of my other posts. TL:DW — I’m a big fan of changing how students think about using AI. Right now, lots of students (and non-students) think it’s a magical cheating machine that does their homework for them. In contrast, I love that Adobe AI Assistant is an AI tool that’s clearly **not** that. Instead, it’s a tool that makes documents interactive in a way that’s especially great for a generation who — like it or not — is growing up with AI and expects to be able to search for things using natural language queries.

Anyway… I realize I could have just deleted your comment and moved on with life, but your reaction is exactly the kind of reaction I considered when I first considered partnering with Adobe, and so this felt like a good opportunity to at least share my thoughts. Truth be told, I’ve had dozens of AI companies reach out and ask me to promote their products, and they all felt like spammy cheating tools so I passed.

I would argue Adobe’s implementation of AI (across their suite of platforms) is one of the examples of AI being used to generate meaningful value for creatives like me, and that seems worth endorsing.

Thank you for reading my TED Talk 😁
